@startuml fig-udp-multicast-flow
skinparam backgroundColor white
skinparam defaultFontName Arial
skinparam defaultFontSize 11
skinparam shadowing false
skinparam sequenceMessageAlign center

title UDP multicast communication (IPv4 group 224.0.0.1)

participant "Sender\nIP_MULTICAST_TTL=32" as S #FFE0B2
participant "Multicast Group\n224.0.0.1:5001" as G #E1BEE7
participant "Receiver A\nIP_ADD_MEMBERSHIP" as RA #C8E6C9
participant "Receiver B\nIP_ADD_MEMBERSHIP" as RB #C8E6C9
participant "Host X\n(not subscribed)" as HX #ECEFF1

== GROUP SUBSCRIPTION ==

RA -[#1565C0]> G : setsockopt(IP_ADD_MEMBERSHIP)
RB -[#1565C0]> G : setsockopt(IP_ADD_MEMBERSHIP)

note over RA, RB
  Receivers join the multicast group
  via IGMP (handled by the kernel).
end note

== DATA DELIVERY ==

S -[#1565C0]> G : sendto("Hello, multicast!",\n224.0.0.1:5001)
G -[#43A047]-> RA : datagram delivered
G -[#43A047]-> RB : datagram delivered
G -[#E53935]->x HX : not delivered\n(not subscribed)

|||

S -[#1565C0]> G : sendto("m2", 224.0.0.1:5001)
G -[#43A047]-> RA : datagram delivered
G -[#43A047]-> RB : datagram delivered

legend right
  Multicast delivers only to hosts that
  have joined the group (class D address).
  The kernel uses IGMP to manage membership.
  Unlike broadcast, non-subscribers do not
  receive the traffic, reducing network load.
  TTL controls the multicast scope (hops).
endlegend
@enduml
